Apple Watch Import Ban
----------------------

From 9to5Mac ( https://9to5mac.com/2023/12/18/apple-halting-apple-watch-ser=
ies-9-and-apple-watch-ultra-2-sales/ ) :

In a statement to 9to5Mac, Apple has announced that it will soon halt sales=
 of its flagship Apple Watch models in the United States. The Apple Watch S=
eries 9 and Apple Watch Ultra 2 will no longer be available to purchase fro=
m Apple starting later this week. The move comes following an ITC ruling as=
 part of a long-running patent dispute between Apple and medical technology=
 company Masimo around the Apple Watch=E2=80=99s blood oxygen sensor techno=
logy.

The Apple Watch Ultra 2 and Apple Watch Series 9 will no longer be availabl=
e to order from Apple=E2=80=99s website in the U.S. after 3 p.m. ET on Thur=
sday, December 21. In-store inventory will no longer be available from Appl=
e retail locations after December 24.

The International Trade Commission announced its ruling in October, upholdi=
ng a judge=E2=80=99s decision from January. This sent the case to the Biden=
 administration for a 60-day Presidential Review Period. During this proces=
s, President Biden could veto the ruling, although this has not yet occurre=
d. The Presidential Review Period expires on December 25, and Apple is maki=
ng this announcement today to =E2=80=9Cpreemptively=E2=80=9D take steps to =
comply with the ITC=E2=80=99s decision.

First off, it certainly is convenient for Apple that the ITC=E2=80=99s ban,=
 if enacted, starts on December 26th; to that end, I think we know what is =
the last day of purchase you can expect products bought on Apple.com to mak=
e it to your house by Christmas! Second, by announcing the imminent halt of=
 sales, Apple not only gets a potential rush to purchase now, but =E2=80=94=
 and I assume this is the primary goal =E2=80=94 gets to put public pressur=
e on the Biden administration to veto the ITC=E2=80=99s order. Third, the I=
TC=E2=80=99s order only applies to imports, and the company doing the impor=
ting; that means that non-Apple retailers can continue to sell already-impo=
rted Apple Watches until they run out of stock.

Apple v Masimo
--------------

So what, exactly, is the ITC, and what is this dispute?

It starts back in 2013; from the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/=
articles/apple-watch-patents-5b52cda0 ) in April of this year, in an articl=
e alleging that Apple regularly offers overtures to smaller companies to le=
arn about their tech, only to steal/invent their own versions of the techno=
logy in question:

Masimo, the developer of blood-oxygen measurement devices, unveiled the mob=
ile pulse oximeter designed to work as an accessory with Apple devices at a=
 trade show in 2013. Adrian Perica, then head of mergers and acquisitions a=
t Apple, told Masimo executives in an email, seen by The Wall Street Journa=
l, that Apple wanted to =E2=80=9Cdig deep=E2=80=9D into Masimo=E2=80=99s te=
chnology and what the company had coming next. =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s discu=
ss any ideas you have about how Apple could or should integrate some [of] t=
hese technologies in our products,=E2=80=9D Mr. Perica wrote.

A few months later, Mr. Kiani said, he got a call from his chief medical of=
ficer, Michael O=E2=80=99Reilly, informing him he was joining Apple, which =
he said had agreed to double his salary and pay him millions in Apple share=
s. Mr. O=E2=80=99Reilly didn=E2=80=99t respond to requests for comment. Mr.=
 Kiani said Apple urged him not to worry about the hiring of Mr. O=E2=80=99=
Reilly, and the two companies continued to talk about potential plans. Appl=
e went on to hire 30 of Masimo=E2=80=99s employees, he said.

In 2014, Apple hired Marcelo Lamego, a former Masimo employee who was chief=
 technical officer at Masimo spinoff company Cercacor Laboratories Inc., wh=
ich licenses Masimo=E2=80=99s technology. In an email before he was hired, =
Mr. Lamego told Mr. Cook that he could =E2=80=9Cadd a significant value=E2=
=80=9D to Apple =E2=80=9Cwithout conflicting with the large IP I have devel=
oped for Masimo and Cercacor during the same period.=E2=80=9D Mr. Lamego di=
dn=E2=80=99t respond to requests for comment.

Masimo responded by filing a lawsuit alleging patent infringement and trade=
 secret violations in federal court, and also an action with the ITC; Apple=
 responded by petitioning the Patent Trial and Appeal Board to invalidate M=
asimo=E2=80=99s patents, and also filed a patent infringement suit against =
Masimo in federal court. What happened next is complicated:

* A federal judge separated Masimo=E2=80=99s trade secret allegations and p=
atent infringement allegations into two cases; the trade secret case procee=
ded and ended in a mistrial ( https://www.reuters.com/legal/us-judge-declar=
es-mistrial-apple-masimo-smartwatch-trade-secrets-fight-2023-05-01/ ) , whi=
le the patent infringement case was put on hold pending Apple=E2=80=99s pet=
ition to the Patent Trial and Appeal Board.
* Apple successfully invalidated ( https://www.reuters.com/legal/litigation=
/us-court-upholds-rulings-apple-masimo-smartwatch-patent-fight-2023-09-12/ =
) a good number of Masimo=E2=80=99s patents in front of the Patent Trial an=
d Appeal Board; those invalidations held up under appeal. However, they did=
n=E2=80=99t invalidate all of them, including the one patent at play in fro=
nt the ITC.
* An ITC administrative judge ruled in favor of Masimo last January ( https=
://news.bloomberglaw.com/ip-law/apple-loses-first-round-of-masimo-bid-to-ba=
n-us-watch-imports ) in the case of that one patent (technically the judge =
ruled that Apple violated three patents, but the other two didn=E2=80=99t s=
atisfy the ITC requirement that it only rule when there is a domestic indus=
try to protect); the ITC tribune then imposed the import ban in October, wh=
ich takes effect in 60 days. However, because the ITC is an executive branc=
h agency, its decisions can be reversed by the President.

So about the ITC: that stands for =E2=80=9CInternational Trade Commission=
=E2=80=9D; it is an independent bipartisan executive branch agency in charg=
e of analyzing trade and directing actions against unfair trade practices, =
including subsidies, dumping, and intellectual property infringement. Its a=
ctions are restricted to products that have a domestic industry that needs =
to be protected. The ITC does not grant monetary rewards =E2=80=94 that is =
why Masimo also filed a case in federal court =E2=80=94 but it is a particu=
larly effective cudgel against a company like Apple that makes all of its p=
roducts abroad.

Apple=E2=80=99s Response
----------------

First off, I have to admit that I was a little too flippant about this case=
 on this morning=E2=80=99s Dithering ( https://dithering.fm ) ; my primary =
point is that it=E2=80=99s hard to feel sympathy for Apple here, given they=
 have gone to the ITC themselves previously to ban the sale of certain Sams=
ung devices ( https://www.itcblog.com/6033-itc-imposes-import-ban-on-popula=
r-samsung-products-in-certain-electronic-digital-media-devices-337-ta-796 )=
 ; Samsung did the same, and while the ITC ruled in Samsung=E2=80=99s favor=
, President Obama vetoed the ban ( https://www.forbes.com/sites/conniegugli=
elmo/2013/08/03/president-obama-vetoes-itc-ban-on-iphone-ipads-apple-happy-=
samsung-not/?sh=3D4b61ddce8c3d ). In other words, Apple has played this gam=
e before, and won; it=E2=80=99s hard to feel bad for them losing here, at l=
east for now, and you can understand why they are angling for another Presi=
dential veto.

That point still stands, but I will say, I think the overall progression of=
 this litigation has largely been reasonable: Masimo is right to defend its=
 intellectual property, and Apple is right to seek to invalidate what it fe=
els are invalid patents. In fact, I=E2=80=99d go further than that: given A=
pple=E2=80=99s relative power and alleged brazen willingness to meet-and-re=
invent =E2=80=94 i.e. investigate partnerships with small companies and the=
n make their own versions =E2=80=94 having a body like the ITC that is uniq=
uely high leverage against an importer like Apple is a good counterbalance =
(this is where I was too flippant on Dithering).

The bigger questions are around the patent system as a whole, both the ease=
 with which patents are often granted and the huge expenses involved in lit=
igating them. I suspect these two points are related, and strike me as a sy=
stemic failure: stringent patent examination that resulted in far fewer but=
 far stronger patents would negate the need for very expensive court cases =
(definitely plural!) to actually figure out if a patent is valid or not, wh=
ich certainly favors larger players.

For now, Mark Gurman reports at Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/=
articles/2023-12-18/apple-plans-rescue-for-17-billion-watch-business-in-fac=
e-of-ban ) that Apple is hoping to work around the problem through software=
:

Apple Inc., just days away from a US ban of its smartwatches, is plotting a=
 rescue mission for the $17 billion business that includes software fixes a=
nd other potential workarounds. Engineers at the company are racing to make=
 changes to algorithms on the device that measure a user=E2=80=99s blood ox=
ygen level =E2=80=94 a feature that Masimo Corp. has argued infringes its p=
atents. They=E2=80=99re adjusting how the technology determines oxygen satu=
ration and presents the data to customers, according to people familiar wit=
h the work=E2=80=A6

Apple could settle with Masimo, though that=E2=80=99s a route it typically =
prefers not to take. And the two companies don=E2=80=99t appear to have eng=
aged on that front. For now, Apple is focused on modifying its technology a=
nd trying to win favor with regulators=E2=80=A6

Work within Apple suggests that the company believes software changes =E2=
=80=94 rather than a more complicated hardware overhaul =E2=80=94 will be e=
nough to bring the device back to store shelves. But the patents at the hea=
rt of the dispute are mostly related to hardware, including how light is em=
itted into the skin to measure the amount of oxygen in a person=E2=80=99s b=
lood. Masimo has said that a software fix will be an insufficient remedy. =
=E2=80=9CThe hardware needs to change,=E2=80=9D the maker of medical device=
s said.

I=E2=80=99m not going to pass judgment on the legitimacy of the patent in q=
uestion (despite the fact that oximeters have been around for a very long t=
ime); I have to admit, though, that I found this report surprising: I assum=
ed that a software fix meant simply disabling the Apple Watch oximeter, as =
opposed to tweaking its algorithm. Obviously Apple doesn=E2=80=99t want to =
have to withdraw a feature on Watches already in the market, but it does se=
em the quickest way to a resolution outside of licensing Masimo=E2=80=99s t=
echnology (which is not clear is a possibility, at least at a price palatab=
le to Apple, and the precedent they don=E2=80=99t want to set).

What does seem clear is that Apple=E2=80=99s continued push into consumer-g=
rade medical-adjacent technologies is not going to be easy: the Apple Watch=
 was actually banned by the ITC previously for its heart rate monitoring ca=
pabilities, but the patents in question were invalidated before the ban too=
k effect. I=E2=80=99m guessing Apple assumed/hoped that would happen this t=
ime, as well, but the big guy doesn=E2=80=99t always win. And honestly, tha=
t=E2=80=99s good.

To that end, I think the Biden administration should not intervene. Say wha=
t you will about Apple v. Samsung, at least that was a U.S. company versus =
a foreign one; this is U.S. on U.S., and I think the courts are doing a pre=
tty good job. Let the process play out.

